Looking back:

- Part 1: {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 7, 9}
- Part 2: {1, 3, 5, 7, 9}

So, they are not equal because part 1 has the element 2 and 4, which part 2 doesn't.

Wait, but in our case:

(A ∩ B) ∪ C = {3,5,7} ∪ {1,2,4,7,9} = {1,2,3,4,5,7,9}

A ∩ (B ∪ C) = A ∩ {1,2,3,4,5,7,9} = {1,3,5,7,9}

So, they are not equal because (A ∩ B) ∪ C includes 2 and 4 from C, which are not in A.
